Is Maryland Basketball Really That Bad at Recruiting Local Talent?¶

In my 2.5 years at UMD, I've regularly listened to my friends lament over how talent-rich the DMV high school basketball scene is and how UMD Basketball fails to recruit the local talent. I wanted to see if this was actually the case. Is Maryland really that bad at recruiting local talent, and how do we stack up compared to other basketball programs? More broadly, I wanted to look at the overall spatial relationship between high school basketball players and the college they ended up attending. Do all colleges have a spatial relationship with their recruits? Which ones do or do not? Ultimately, this analysis can give me better insight into the dynamics of college recruiting and whether or not I should tell my friends to stop complaining and actually be proud of Maryland Basketball's home town traditions.

Part 1: Data Scraping - DO NOT RUN SCRAPER: THE WEBSITE HAS CHANGED¶

To find out which schools are good at recruiting local talent, I needed a dataset of college basketball recruits. 247sports.com is the leading website for tracking high school football and basketball players as they transition to college. Each year, they list the top 5, 4, and 3 star basketball recruits along with other data including their high school and college. With the locations of each recruits home town and college, I could look at the spatial relationship between colleges and their recruits.

Now it's time to scrape. I looped through each year from 2011 to 2022 (inclusive), and plugged that number into the 247 sports url to scrape the right page (this is now different, they removed some rankings). Then I looped through each ranking li item and extracted all relevant information including graduating class, class rank, name, home town, position, stars (3, 4, or 5), score (247 sports generated score out of 100), and college. Using the home town content, I also extracted the city and state individually, and I used the state abbreviation dictionary to create address, a column containing the full city and state name. For example, if the hometown was "College Park, MD", the city would be "College Park", state "MD", and address "College Park, Maryland". If all of the above fields existed, the recruit was from the US, and committed to a US school, I added him to the dictionary.

In [15]:
# Iterate through all recruiting years from 2011 to 2022
for year in range (2011, 2023):
    
    # Use beautiful soup to find rankings from 247 sports
    URL = "https://247sports.com/Season/" + str(year) + "-Basketball/RecruitRankings/?InstitutionGroup=HighSchool"
    headers = {"User-Agent": "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/89.0.4389.90 Safari/537.36"}
    page = requests.get(URL, headers=headers)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page.content, "html.parser")
    main_content = soup.find("ul", {"class" : "rankings-page__list"})
    rankings = main_content.find_all("li", {"class": "rankings-page__list-item"})
    
    # Iterate through each item
    for ranking in rankings:
        
        # Get the player's ranking
        r_string = ranking.find("div", class_="primary").text.strip()[:3]
        rank = re.search("[0-9]+", r_string)
        if(rank != None):
            rank = rank.group(0)
        
        # Get the name of the player
        name = ranking.find("a", class_= "rankings-page__name-link").text.strip()
        
        # Extract the player's home town (from the high school) as well as the city and state name
        h_string = ranking.find("span", class_= "meta").text.strip()
        h_string = h_string[h_string.find("(")+1:h_string.find(")")]
        home_town = re.search(".+, [A-Z]{2}\Z", h_string)
        if(home_town != None):
            home_town = home_town.group(0)
            city = home_town.split(",")[0].strip()
            state = home_town.split(",")[1].strip()
            
        # Create a full address based on the home town name
        if(city!= None and state != None and state in states):
            abbrs_backwards = dict((abbrs[full_name], full_name) for full_name in abbrs)
            full_state = abbrs_backwards[state]
            address = city + ", " + full_state
            
        # Extract the player's position
        position = ranking.find("div", class_="position").text.strip()
        
        # Extract the player's number of stars (3, 4, or 5)
        stars = len(ranking.find_all("span", class_="icon-starsolid yellow"))
        
        # Extract the players score
        score = ranking.find("span", class_="score").text.strip()
        
        # Extract the name of the college the player is attending
        college = ranking.find("div", class_ = "status").find("img", class_ = "jsonly")
        
        # If all of the above variables exist, the recruit is from the US, and they committed to a US college, add them to the dictionary
        if(year != None and 
                   rank != None and 
                   name != None and 
                   city != None and
                   state != None and
                   home_town != None and 
                   address != None and
                   position != None and 
                   stars != None and
                   score != None and
                   college != None and 
                   college != "Professional" and
                   state in states):
            recruitDict["class"].append(str(year))
            recruitDict["rank"].append(rank)
            recruitDict["name"].append(name)
            recruitDict["city"].append(city)
            recruitDict["state"].append(state)
            recruitDict["home_town"].append(home_town)
            recruitDict["address"].append(address)
            recruitDict["position"].append(position)
            recruitDict["stars"].append(stars)
            recruitDict["score"].append(score)
            recruitDict["college"].append(college["alt"])

Next, I converted the dictionary into a Pandas DataFrame. In total, there are 2,420 recruits in my dataset, however, since I first wrote this program, 247sports has changed their website, removing rankings for players in 2012-2014.

In [16]:
# Create a pandas DataFrame from the dictionary
df = pd.DataFrame(recruitDict)

In order to conduct a location based analysis, I needed latitude and longitude coordinates. I used the Nominatim library, an open source geo-coding tool that uses Open Street Map. For each of the recruits in the data frame, I passed their home town into the geolocator and created two new columns, "h_lat" and "h_lon" to store the home town latitude and longitude information. I then used the latitude and longitude columns to create a geometry column which was necessary to turn the data frame into a geo data frame, using the geopandas library.

In [2]:
# Create geolocator
geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="gworthin")
In [17]:
# Find the coordinates of the home towns (This block will take half an hour to execute)
locations = df["home_town"].apply(lambda address: geolocator.geocode(address))
In [21]:
# Add the home town latitude and longitude to the DataFrame
df["h_lat"] = locations.apply(lambda x: x.latitude if (x != None) else np.NaN)
df["h_lon"] = locations.apply(lambda x: x.longitude if (x != None) else np.NaN)
In [22]:
# Create a GeoDataFrame from the DataFrame using the home town latitude and longitude as the geometry
geometry = [Point(pos) for pos in zip(df['h_lon'], df['h_lat'])]
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, geometry=geometry)

Part 2: Locating Colleges¶

Now that I located all the home towns, the next step was to locate the colleges. However, this was trickier than the home towns because I didn't have an city and state name to pass into the geolocater. For example, 247sports simply labels the University of Maryland as "Maryland". If I tried to pass "Maryland" into the geolocater, I'm not sure what coordinates it would give me, but it definitly wouldn't be in College Park. Although tedious, I didn't see a better way to solve this issue than to manually write out the full name of every college that appeared in the dataframe. I downloaded the recruits_with_home_towns.dbf file and opened it in Excel. I found the unique colleges and with just I few exceptions appended "University of" to the begining, or "College" or "University" to the end. For the scope of this project, doing every college ended up being a bit of overkill, but it's valueable data I can use in future analysis. Ultimately, I was able to create the colleges dictionary seen below, mapping each of the 247sports names to the full name that could be used by the geolocator.

Part 3: Data Cleanup¶

The last step before I started my data analysis was to clean up any lingering errors. For a number of home towns and a few colleges, the geolocator was able to find a latitude and longitude for the address I provided, but it was just in the wrong spot. I found the error towns by extracting latitude and longitudes outside of the US. I found the error colleges through plotting in the next section and noticing they were in the right state but not quite the right wrong spot.

Local Area Analysis¶

Now comes the big question: how does one define a "local area" or "home town"? Is it the town the college is in? The county? Maybe the state? Is a UMD recruit from Baltimore a local one? What about from Northern Virginia? The truth is there is no concrete answer and it is different for each college. As hard as it is to come up with an answer to that question in plain english, it's even more difficult to answer it using code. However, I think my solution makes the best of a tricky situation. I knew I didn't want to use a set distance as the local area, for example a circle of 50 miles around a college. This could exclude recruits who would see themselves a local in sprawling metro areas like LA or isolated colleges like Gonzaga, and it could group together dense and nearby metro areas like New York and Philadelphia. I also didn't want to define local area based on which college each recruit was closest to, because for UCLA and USC, this would divide up LA even though all recruits in the city should be considered local for both colleges. Ultimately, I decided to define a "local area" as the 100 nearest recruits to the college. There are 2,420 observations in my dataset, and when plotted on the map, they resemble the population distribution of the U.S. By defining "local area" based on this distribution, the size and shape of the 100 nearest recruits to the University of Maryland would look very different to those of the University of Utah's, and the University of Arkansas's for example. This method was the best way I could think of to define "local" differently for each college, and following the population distribution of the United States.

In [15]:
# Function takes a point associated with a college and returns a geodataframe containing the n nearest recruits to that point.
def get_n_nearest(college_point, n):
    
    ht_list = list(gdf_h["h_geometry"])
    name_list = list(gdf_h["name"])
    
    # Lists to keep track of nearest points (home towns), names (to keep track of unique observations because many players 
    # are from the same place) and distance to make sure we have the nearest 100
    nearest_points = []
    nearest_names = []
    smallest_distances = []
    
    # Iterate through every home town point in the home town list.
    i = 0
    for home_town in ht_list:
        
        # Calculate distance from home town to college
        cur_dist = college_point.distance(home_town)
        
        # If we haven't found n points yet, append the point to the points list, player name to the names list, and distance 
        # to the distances list
        if(len(nearest_points) < n):
            nearest_points.append(home_town)
            nearest_names.append(name_list[i])
            smallest_distances.append(cur_dist)
            
        
        else:
            
            # Check if this home town is closer than one of the points already in the list, if so, replace it
            cur_max_of_small_distances = max(smallest_distances)
            if(cur_max_of_small_distances > cur_dist):
                index = smallest_distances.index(cur_max_of_small_distances)
                nearest_points[index] = home_town
                smallest_distances[index] = cur_dist
                nearest_names[index] = name_list[i]
        i += 1
        
    # Return geodataframe with the names and locations of the 100 nearest recruits to the college
    return gpd.GeoDataFrame({'name':nearest_names,'h_geometry':nearest_points}, geometry="h_geometry")

Now that I defined a local area, I needed a way to measure how good a college was at recruiting from said area. The first and most obvious metric was just counting how many players in the local area actually went to that college. That is, how many of the 100 nearest recruits to the college actually attended. This number however would be dependent on how many total recruits a college got in the last 11 years. For example, a school like Indiana who recruited 40 players could theoretically recruit more from their local area and a school like Minnesota, with only 20 recruits. So this metric, the "Number of Recruits from Local Area", not only measures how good a school is at recruiting locally, but also how good a school is at recruiting in general. I wanted another metric that wouldn't be affected by a schools total number of recruits. So I chose to aslo calculate the "Percent of Recruits who are Local" by dividing the number above by the schools total recruits over the past 11 years. For example, Maryland recruited 12 local players and 26 total players in the last 11 years and 12/26 = 46.2% of total recruits who are local. This metric looks at how *dependent* a team is on their local talent by asking: how much of their roster is from the surrounding area?

In [16]:
# Function finds both of the above mentioned metrics: Number of Recruits from Local Area, and Percent of Recruits who are Local
# Takes in a shapely point with the college's coordinates and an n representing the number of recruits that constitute a local 
# area and returns a tuple containing both metrics
def find_n_nearest_recruits_data(point, n):
    
    # Get geodataframe of the n nearest players to the college
    gdf_n_closest = get_n_nearest(point, n) 
    # Merge with gdf storing all data by name and home town geometry
    gdf_n_closest = pd.merge(gdf_n_closest, gdf, on=["name", "h_geometry"], how="inner")
    
    # Find the name of the college
    college = gdf_colleges_20[gdf_colleges_20["geometry"] == point]["college"].values[0]
    
    # Number of recruits in the local area who attended the college is just the number in the gdf whose college matches 
    # the point
    num_recruits_from_nearest_100 = len(gdf_n_closest[gdf_n_closest["college"] == college])
    
    # Percent of recruits who are local is calculated by dividing the previous column by the number of recruits in the 
    # colleges geodataframe
    pct_recruits_who_are_local = num_recruits_from_nearest_100 / gdf_colleges_20[gdf_colleges_20["college"] == 
                                                                                 college]["recruits"].values[0]
    
    # Return both numbers as a tuple
    return (num_recruits_from_nearest_100, pct_recruits_who_are_local)

In-State Analysis¶

Another logical defition of local area could just be the in-state recruits. It's plausible that high school basketball players in California for example, would want to play for a recognizable California university like UCLA even if they weren't from the LA area. So in this analysis, instead of defining local area as the 100 nearest recruits, this time I defined it as the state the college was located in. I calculated the same metrics as last time: the number of in-state recruits, and the percentage of recruits who were in-state.

Distance Significance Testing¶

The last thing I wanted to include was some sort of signifigance test on the clustering of recruits around a college. I wanted to ask the question: "is the distribution of recruits significantly clustered around their college?" There are many different ways to conduct point pattern analysis, but to my knowledge, they all fail in two key areas. First, I couldn't find an existing method that would take into account the existing population distribution behind the spatial pattern of the recruits. For example, having a bunch of recruits clustered around New York city doesn't necessarily mean anything significant, because a lot of recruits are from there anyway. Secondly, I also needed a way to test the clustering relationship of the recruits not with each other, but around a central point: the college. To satisfy both the afformentioned requirements, I created my own technique for point pattern analysis. Take Maryland for example. Maryland has 26 3, 4, or 5 star recruits from the past 11 years. For each of those 26 recruits, I found the distance from their hometown to UMD and stored those 26 distances in a list. Then, I picked 26 *random* recruits from the entire dataset of 2,420, and found their distances to UMD. I then conducted a ztest on the two lists to see how likely it was that the set of distances of the actual set of recruits could have come from a random distribution.

In [30]:
# Function takes an array of points and a destination point and returns a list of distances from each point in the array to 
# the destination point
def get_avg_dist(points_arr, dest_point):
    distances = []
    for p in points_arr:
        distances.append(shapely.geometry.Point(p).distance(dest_point))
    return distances
In [31]:
# Function takes a college string and runs and returns the ztest on the list of distances from each recruit to the college
# and a set of random recruits to that college
def z_test(college):
    
    # Get hometowns of the colleges recruits
    hometowns = list(gdf_h[gdf_h["college"] == college]["h_geometry"].values)
    # Get the college point
    college_point = gdf_c[gdf_c["college"] == college].geometry.iloc[0]
    # Get the distances from the recruits to the college
    distances = get_avg_dist(hometowns,college_point)
    
    # Pick n random points and create the list of distances
    points = []
    for i in range(len(hometowns)):
        rand = random.randint(0, len(gdf_h)-1)
        points.append(gdf_h.iloc[rand]["h_geometry"])
    rand_distances = get_avg_dist(points, college_point)
    
    # Return ztest
    return ztest(rand_distances, distances)

Because the distribution of random points is different every time, I run the ztest on 50 sets of random points for each college and create columns of the average and median p-values

In [32]:
# Initial lists
avg_p_values = []
med_p_values = []
colleges = list(gdf_colleges_20["college"])

# For each college
for college in colleges:
    
    # Run 50 ztests
    college_p_vals = []
    for i in range(0,50):
        college_p_vals.append(z_test(college)[1])
    college_p_vals.sort()
    
    # Find the average and median z tests
    avg_p_values.append(sum(college_p_vals)/len(college_p_vals))
    med_p_values.append((college_p_vals[24] + college_p_vals[25]) / 2)
    
# Create a new dataframe with the college name and their average and median p-values
df_p = pd.DataFrame({"college":colleges,"cluster_avg_p_value":avg_p_values,"cluster_med_p_value":med_p_values})

# Add boolean column for significant or not significant
df_p["cluster_avg_significant"] = df_p["cluster_avg_p_value"] < 0.05
df_p["cluster_med_significant"] = df_p["cluster_med_p_value"] < 0.05

Maps¶

It doesn't make any sense to do all of this locational analysis without making any maps. Below I defined 3 functions to take in the name of a college as a string and plot a map related to one of the three above metrics. The first displays the college, its recruits, and its local area. The second displays the college, its recruits and its state. The third displays the college, its recruits, and the rest of the 2,420 recruits, to emphasize the existance or non-existance of a clustering relationship. These functions allow me to produce maps for the discussion and further analysis

In [38]:
# Function takes a string with a college name and plots the college, its local area, and its recruits over the U.S.
def plot_college_local_data(college):
    
    # Get geodataframe of 100 nearest nearest recruits and create a convex hull from the points
    n=100
    gdf_n_closest = get_n_nearest(gdf_colleges_20[gdf_colleges_20['college'] == college]['geometry'].values[0], n)  
    gdf_n_closest = pd.merge(gdf_n_closest, gdf, on=["name", "h_geometry"], how="inner")
    hull_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry = [gdf_n_closest.unary_union.convex_hull]).set_crs(4326)
    
    # Get the college's recruits
    gdf_recruits = gdf_h[gdf_h["college"] == college]
        
    # Get the college point
    gdf_college = gdf_colleges_20[gdf_colleges_20["college"] == college]
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30,30))
    # Plot states
    states.plot(ax=ax,
            color='whitesmoke',
            edgecolor='black',
            linewidth=0.2)
    # Plot local area
    hull_gdf.plot(ax=ax,
                  markersize=2,
                  color="grey", 
                  alpha = 0.5)
    # Plot recruits
    gdf_recruits.plot(ax=ax, 
                      markersize=35,
                     color="red")
    # Plot college
    gdf_college.plot(ax=ax,
                     markersize=35,
                    color="blue")  
    
    # Get number of recruits from the local area and the percent of recruits who are local
    nrn100 = gdf_colleges_20.loc[gdf_colleges_20["college"] == college]["num_recruits_from_nearest_100"].values[0]
    pctlocal = gdf_colleges_20.loc[gdf_colleges_20["college"] == college]["pct_recruits_who_are_local"].values[0]
    
    # Display title
    plt.title(college + "\nNumber of Recruits From Local Area: " + str(nrn100) + "\nPercent of " + str(college) + 
              " Recruits who are Local: " + str(pctlocal.round(3)), fontdict={'fontsize': 20})

# Function takes a college and plots its recruits on top of all the recruits to visualize the spatial clustering
def plot_college_cluster_data(college):
    
    # Get the recruits
    gdf_recruits = gdf_h[gdf_h["college"] == college]    
    
    # Get the college point
    gdf_college = gdf_colleges_20[gdf_colleges_20["college"] == college]
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30,30))
    # Plot states
    states.plot(ax=ax,
            color='floralwhite',
            edgecolor='black',
            linewidth=0.2)
    # Plot all recruits' hometowns
    gdf_h.plot(ax=ax,
               markersize=1,
               color="grey",
               alpha=0.8)
    # Plot college's recruits
    gdf_recruits.plot(ax=ax, 
                      markersize=35,
                     color="red",
                     alpha=1)
    # Plot college
    gdf_college.plot(ax=ax,
                     markersize=50,
                    color="blue")  
    
    # Display title
    plt.title(college + "\nAverage p-value for z test comparing list of distances from recruits to college vs list of " + 
              "distances from a random set of recruit points to college: " + 
              str(gdf_colleges_20[gdf_colleges_20["college"]==college]["cluster_avg_p_value"].values[0].round(10)), 
              fontdict={'fontsize': 20})
    plt.show()

The original question was all about Maryland so lets see how Maryland did. In the maps above you can see all 6 of the relevant metrics but here they are again:

Maryland was only able to recruit 12 of the 100 nearest high school basketball players who went on the play D1 basketball in the last 11 years. If we told my friends this, they might see this as proof that we suck at recruiting locally. 12 of 100 doesn't sound like a lot. However, when compared to all the other colleges in the analysis, that isn't half bad. Additionally, when considering that we only recruited 26 total players in that same time period, that means 46% or nearly half of our 3, 4, and 5 star recruits could be considered local. That was a lot better than I was expecting when I started this project. In terms of the in-state analysis, 11 of those 12 local recruits were from Maryland state (one local player was from NoVa). Meanwhile, Maryland had a very significant clustering relationship between the recruits' hometowns and their colleges, a relationship that is readily apparant in each of the above maps. Even for the non-local recruits, they came from Philadelphia or New England, with a few from other parts of the southern and eastern parts of the United States. Notably, we have no recruits from the West Coast, all together making it very unlikely this spatial distribution was random. So those are the raw numbers, but how did Maryland stack up compared to other colleges? Were they any better at recruiting locally?

In comparison to the 56 other colleges in the dataset, Maryland ranked high in both the local area and in-state metrics. Maryland was tied with Michigan for 10th on the number of recruits from the local area list. Our highest place on any list was 6th on the percent of recruits who are local list. This can be interpreted as Maryland being exceptionally reliant on recruiting local talent when compared to other colleges in the United States. We are also near the top of the lists for the in-state metrics, though not as high as in the local area analyses. This makes sense because Maryland is a small state so while schools in states like California, Texas, Georgia, and Florida had the ability to recruit players from their state who might not have been in their local area, Maryland did not. There are simply less people in the state so most of Maryland was already captured by the local area. Interestingly, for both the local area and in-state analyses, we ranked higher compared to other colleges in the percentage metric than the raw number metric. This makes sense because the number metrics take into account how good the school is at recruiting in general and Maryland is one of the worse recruiting schools in this dataset. Additionally, the fact that our percents are generally higher seems to indicate that even if we don't recruit an exceptionally high number of players from the DMV, we are more reliant on our local talent than other schools. Let's take a look at some other notable colleges, specifically Alabama, who topped the list for number of local recruits.

Alabama recruited a whopping 19 of their 100 nearest recruits in the last 10 years, with plenty of competition from neighboring schools like Auburn, Georgia, and Mississippi State. They rank high on all metrics I calculated (higher than Maryland), and have a very significant clustering relationship. I find this school particularly interesting, because Alabama has gone through four head coaches during this time period. I always thought the head coach had a major role in recruiting players, and assumed maybe one coach in particular had unlocked the secret to getting players to stay home. Instead, there must be some other factors at play, like maybe a proud state with a storied basketball tradition or a solid infrastructure of local scouts.

Meanwhile, Texas A&M has a very obvious in-state relationship. There are two huge clusters of recruits from Dallas and Houston. Amazingly, two thirds of their recruits in the last 11 years were from the state of Texas. While high on the in-state lists, Texas A&M wasn't as high up on the local area lists because their local area included Houston but failed to caputer the Dallas area. Like most schools in this analysis, Texas A&M exhibited a significant relationship in the clustering analysis.

What I find just as interesting however, are the schools that failed to exhibit significant clusting relationships, with a group of recruits that might as well have been random. The three colleges with the most recruits in the last 11 years, Kentucky, Duke, and Kansas, all failed to exhibit statistically significant clustering. Additionally, all 3 ranked low compared to other colleges in their ability to recruit (and their reliance on) local area and in state recruits.

When looking at Kentucky's map, it might as well be random. There are players from every major population center: New York, LA, Chicago, Atlanta, Houston, and they exhibit a similar distribution to that of the grey dots in the map: the 2,420 total recruits. It might be that Kentucky, Duke, and Kansas, are so successful that they don't have to concern themselves on recruiting locally, they can just find the best of the best, no matter where they are from. Of the last 10 NCAA champions (not 11 because of COVID-19 in 2020), there are 9 unique winners because Villanova won twice. 5 of those 9: Kentucky, Louisville, Duke, Virginia, and most recently Kansas, did not have significant clustering relationships. That's a majority of NCAA champions during the same time period as this analysis without a significant clustering relationship compared to only 35% of this dataset. It might be that in order to win, you should to be able to recruit from the whole country. On the flip side, Arkansas could arguably have the most obvious spatial relationship with its recruits.

Limitations¶

As previously mentioned, my definition of "local area" was far from perfect, and there are some issues I just can't fix. Let's take a look at Georgia and Oklahoma State.

In [51]:
plot_college_local_data("Oklahoma State")
In [52]:
plot_college_local_data("Georgia")

Both schools have incredibly obvious spatail relationships. In Oklahoma State's case, there's a Dallas-to-Stillwater basketball pipeline, and Georgia recruits a significant number of players from the Greater Atlanta Area. However in both cases, the local area analysis fails to fully capture all the recruits from these areas. 50% of OSU's recruits were from their local area but judging by the map you could argue it was even higher. Alternatively, you could also argue that Dallas shouldn't be considered local for Oklahoma State. After all, it's a 4 hour drive between the two cities. There is no right answer to whether or not Dallas should be considered local for OSU, and even if there was, how could I translate it to code in a way the fairly preserved local areas for everyone else? Anyways, while half of their recruits were classified as local, only 25% were in-state. Even with an obvious spatial relationship from the map, these two metrics are wildly different. In Georgia's case, it's the opposite. 22% of their recruits were local meanwhile 55% of their recruits were in-state. Which metric is better? It's different for each college. Both OSU and Georgia had statistically significant clustering between their recruits and the college, but the story is always incomplete without each of the 3 analyses and the map to paint the full picture. All three analyses, local area, in-state, and clustering, are flawed, but put together we can start to see the trends that emerge. Finally, another major limitation that seems almost impossible to overcome without access to another dataset is that a number of recruits will go to boarding schools to play high school basketball. There are a number of schools like Montverde, Oak Hill, and IMG Academy, who recruit high school players from around the country. On 247sports, this shows up as their hometown. I'm sure for some students, if you asked them where they were from, they wouldn't say the home town listed on 247sports. However, I doubt that the number of students who move for high school ultimately doesn't affect this analysis too much, but it does again raise the question as what counts as a home town and what counts as a local area.

Further Research¶

No analysis ever feels complete, but with this one especially I can think of all sorts of questions I'd like to pursue if I had the time. I'd love to factor in the number of stars a recruit has into the local area analysis. Is Maryland recruiting local 3, 4, or 5 star plays at different rates? I'd also love dive deeper into the question of performance and local recruiting. Do schools actually perform better (i.e. win more games or win March Madness) if they recruit more or less locally? And finally I'd like to flip it around and look at it from the players side of things. Are there certain types of players (# of stars, graduation class, home town) who are more or less likely to stay home and play for a local college or go across the country? The possibilities are endless and each question opens the door for ten others.

Final Conclusion¶

Looking at the results from the other colleges is interesting but let's go back and finally answer our original question: Is Maryland really that bad at recruiting local talent? Surprisingly (at least to me and my roommates) the answer is no. When comparing Maryland to 56 other high-recruiting D1 colleges, we are fairly above average on all metrics I created to measure local recruiting. We recruited 12 players from our local area in the past 11 years and 46% of our players are from there. 11 of them came from Maryland or 42% of our total recruits. Each of these numbers is higher than the averages of the other colleges in the dataset, and in my clustering analysis, I found a significant relationship between the distances from the recruits to Maryland, indicating that the spaital pattern of recruits' hometowns could not have been random. Additionally, along the way, I've found a number of other interesting relationships between certain colleges and the locations of their recruits, and I've opened the door for a many analyses that I'll pursue in the future. So yes, as Maryland students we should be proud of the amount of talent we have here in the DMV and the amount of players we already convince to stay home. However, that doesn't mean we can't keep improving, and hopefully during the Kevin Willard era, every DMV high school basketball player will have Maryland #1 on their list.
